Question A (15 pts)

1. Basic calculation in R. (5 pts)

\(x_s = (x_{s1}, \dots, x_{sn})\) and \(w_s = (w_{s1}, \dots, w_{sn})\) (\(s = 1,2,3,4\)) are vectors defined in the R code below. We want to calculate \(\sum_i^n(x^2_{si}/w^2_{si})\) where \(i\) is the element index. Using Map/mapply function to achieve this calculation for all s. Note you need to return a vector instead of a list.

set.seed(32611)
xs <- replicate(4, runif(10), simplify = FALSE)
ws <- replicate(4, rpois(10, 5) + 1, simplify = FALSE)

fnc <- function(x,y){
  sum((x^2)/(y^2))
}

vec <- mapply(fnc, xs, ws)

vec
## [1] 0.12287607 0.25760407 0.09971106 0.10838334

2. Find the intersection recursively using Reduce() function. (5 pts)

In other word, find the element(s) that appear in all 5 lists of vectors.

k <- 5
set.seed(32611)
alist <- replicate(k,sample(k,5,replace = TRUE), simplify = FALSE)

Reduce(intersect, alist)
## [1] 1

3. Replicate Huber function figure. (5 pts)

In HW1, we have seen the Huber function https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huber_loss: \[ f(x) = \begin{cases} x^2 & \text{if $|x| \leq 1$} \\ 2|x| - 1 & \text{if $|x| > 1$} \end{cases} \]

The Huber function is quadratic in the interval [-1, 1] (red line in the figure below) and linear outside the interval (blue line in the figure below). The transitioning between these two curves is smooth as you can verify from the derivatives.

Please reproduce the figure above. Note that you need x axis label x; y axis label f(x); x axis range (-2,2); title Huber, the quadratic part in the interval [-1, 1] is in red color and linear part outside the interval is in blue color. You dont need to worry about the margin if the figure doesnt perfectly match the above figure.

fncv <- function(x){
  ifelse(
    abs(x)<=1, x^2, 2*abs(x)-1
  )
}

curve(fncv, from = -1, to = 1, main="Huber", xlab="x", ylab="f(x)", col = "2", xlim=c(-2,2), ylim=c(0,3))
curve(fncv, from = 1, to = 2, col = "4", add = TRUE)
curve(fncv, from = -2, to = -1, col = "4", add = TRUE)

Question B (45 pts)

The Iris flower data set https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iris_flower_data_set is a multivariate data set introduced by the famous statistician Ronald Fisher. The data set consists of 50 samples from each of three species of Iris (Iris setosa, Iris virginica and Iris versicolor). Four features were measured from each sample: the length and the width of the sepals and petals, in centimetres.

Iris data is available in R data(iris), with total 150 samples. Please answer the following questions:

1. Calculate the mean of Petal.Length by Species (5 pts).

data(iris)

iris %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  summarize(
    "Mean Petal Length" = mean(Petal.Length)
  )

iris %>%

3. For each of the four features, calculate the difference between maximum value and the minimum value (5 pts)

The results will be a vector of four elements (naturally ordered by 1. Sepal.Length, 2. Sepal.Width, 3. Petal.Length and 4, Petal.Width).

df <- iris %>% 
    
  summarise(
    a = (max(Sepal.Length) - min(Sepal.Length)),
    b = (max(Sepal.Width) - min(Sepal.Width)),
    c = (max(Petal.Length) - min(Petal.Length)),
    d = (max(Petal.Width) - min(Petal.Width))
  )
  
c(t(df))
## [1] 3.6 2.4 5.9 2.4

4. Divide each of the four features by the maximum value of the feature. (5 pts)

We end up with a matrix of the same dimension (150, 4) as the original matrix but after this standardization step, all values range between 0 and 1. Use the sweep() function. Only print the first 6 rows of your result.

iris %>% 
    
  summarize(
    "Sepal Length/Max" = Sepal.Length / max(Sepal.Length),
    "Sepal Width/Max" = Sepal.Width / max(Sepal.Width),
    "Petal Length/Max" = Petal.Length / max(Petal.Length),
    "Petal Width/Max" = Petal.Width / max(Petal.Width)
  ) %>% 
  slice(1:6)

5.Correlation heatmap (5 pts)

For each pairs of samples, calculate their Pearson correlation using cor() function. (Try to see if you can avoid loops.). You will get a 150 by 150 matrix. Visualize the correlation matrix by heatmap. In the correlation heatmap, keep the same sample order as the original data matrix. Avoid your function automatically standardizes each row to mean 0 and sd 1. Correlation heatmap is a good diagnostic tool to visualize the similarity among samples. The diagonal lines have correlation 1 since these are samples correlation with themselves. From this figure, you can see which two species are more similar.

library(gplots)

iriscor <- cor(t(iris[,1:4]), method = "pearson")
  
heatmap.2(iriscor, trace= "none", scale = "none", Colv=NA, Rowv=NA, main = "Correlation Heatmap")

Question C (35 pts)

We want to investigate and visualize the diamonds data! A dataset containing the prices and other attributes of almost 54,000 diamonds is included in R ggplot2 package, including carat, color, clarity, cut, total depth, table, depth, width, height and price.

You need to install the ggplot2 package first. The load the diamonds data in R by:

library(ggplot2)
data(diamonds)

For details, check ?diamonds. There are total 53940 diamonds, and we will only work on the subset of diamonds with the best clarity (clarity == IF).

diamonds.subset <- subset(x = diamonds, subset = clarity == "IF")

This will reduce to 1790 diamonds. Again, only work on diamonds.subset throughout this question, you are required to use ggplot() function to generate figures.

1. Draw scattered plot of carat (x-axis) versus price (y-axis). Use the color variable as the color aesthetic mapping (5 pts)

ggplot(diamonds.subset) +
  aes(x = carat, y = price, color = color) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Carat vs Price")

2. Based on question 1, wrap the figures by color (5 pts)

You will end up with 7 sub-figures, with each sub-figure representing the scattered plot of carat versus price for a color. Any facet style is OK.

ggplot(diamonds.subset) +
  aes(x = carat, y = price, color = color) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap( ~ color) +
  labs(title = "Carat vs Price")

3. Based on question 1, use the volumn (\(x\times y \times z\)) as the size aesthetic mapping (5 pts)

Also, label the point with the largest carat value within each color group as H-Color using red color. For example, if the color is D, label the point as H-D with red color in the figure, etc. If there are multiple maximums, you can either mark one of them, or mark all of them.

ds <- diamonds.subset %>% 
  mutate(size = (x*y*z)) %>% 
  group_by(color) %>% 
  mutate(max = max(size)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(label = ifelse(size < max, "", paste0("H-",color)))

ggplot(ds) +
  aes(x = carat, y = price, size = size, color =  color, label=max(rownames(diamonds.subset))) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_label_repel(aes(label=label), color="red", size=3.5) +
  labs(title = "Carat vs Price")

5. Investigate the price/carat ratio by color. (5 pts)

Create boxplot of price/carat ratio by color. Use color variable as the color aesthetic mapping. Also put jittered dots on top of the boxplot, and set the transparent level of the jittered dots as 0.5.

ggplot(diamonds.subset) +
  aes(x = color, y = (price/carat), color = color) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter(alpha=.5) +
  labs(title = "Price/Carat Ratio by Color")

6. Draw histogram of the price, fill by cut (aesthetic option), wrap by color (5 pts)

Use black white (bw) theme. The price value (i.e., the number on the x-axis) should be vertical instead of the default horizontal.

ggplot(diamonds.subset) +
  aes(x=price, bins=20) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill=cut)) +
  facet_wrap(~ color) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)) +
  labs(title = "Price-Cut Histogram")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

7. Draw barplot of color count, fill by cut (aesthetic option). Also use position=dodge such that within each color, different cuts will be placed side by side. (5 pts)

Also, you need to flip x-axis and y-axis for this barplot.

ggplot(diamonds.subset) +
  aes(x=color, bins=20) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=cut), position="dodge") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Color-Cut Barplot")
